<font color="#FF0000">THE KINGDOM OF AU LAC</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jun 28 22:27:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Dear Tom:<br><br>
The war in Viet Nam was never a civil war. the people were suffering because of communist agression before we were called upon to help. Any Vietnamese living in America today will gladly share with you how much they appreciated our intervention. Spent some time speaking to the Vietnamese in our country today, we can still learn a lot about Viet Nam from them. You may also find out why you were never given a hero's welcome when you came into their villages. Perhaps it was because the village individual that did greet you with a smile would have eliminated anyone displaying any support toward us. A lot also had to do with a culture we did not understand and many of us till this day have never tried to understand. It wasn't the North against the Diem government or those who represented a small, elite ruling class. I was there when over 85% of the population freely voted for whom they desired to govern them in 1967. The South had her free election the North never did. You mentioned that the Viet Cong were South Vietnamese - not &quot;invaders&quot; from the North. They were widely supported in the countryside. Nothing can be further from the truth. Allow me to share with you a story Uncle To an old Vietnamese elder once shared with us. I have since seen a similar legion printed in several books about the history of Vietnam.<br><br>
&quot;The people of Viet Nam are all one people we are one with the people of old China. About 5000 years ago we all had the same parents. All the Vietnamese are one family, we are all the grandchildren of  Dragon Lord, Lac Long Quang, the great sea warrior and the beautiful mountain fairy Au Co. <br>
Soon after they were married, Au Co hatched one hundred golden eggs from which one hundred handsome and strong sons were born. But the marriage did not last and they soon parted. Fifty of the oldest sons, the strongest warriors of the clan went with the mother to live in the high northern mountains of China.  There they conquered many people and places. <br>
The eldest son, Hong Bang, being the first born came south with the youngest sons. These were peace loving children, farmers who cleared the jungles and loved to work with their hands and to cultivate the land God had given them. They were unlike their warrior brothers who remained in the North. <br>
Hong Bang called it the kingdom Au Lac, in honor of their parents, and established Viet Nam's first dynasty. Today we still call this land &quot;the little dragon.&quot; The people of China do not know this, they have forgotten that we are brothers, that we have all come from the same parents. They have come to slay the little dragon, but because we have the same parents, we will survive. Our will is to survive.  To live and plant our rice in peace. That is what we wish. To eat meals with our family that has come from our garden.<br>
In the end, we will be free because our parents chose to be free from each other. They are our true ancestors. They are still with us and they will for us to be two separate nations. There will be no real peace in the land of the Little Dragon until the land and the people honor this.&quot; <br><br>
For two years following the 1954 Geneva agreement (which the US never supported) an exodus occurred with the Communist soldiers going North and those desiring freedom South. Ho Chi Minh however kept sleepers in the south and told them to wait until after the election that was suppose to unify Viet Nam as one country. But before that date, the North now controlled By China and Russia backed off and no election was held. The south did the same. A purging occurred on both sides then Ho started to move his troops into the south. They forced villagers to join them or suffer death. VC means Vietnamese Communist the term was given them by the villagers not the US government.  If you want to know what you were up against let me recommend an outstanding book by Michael Lee Lanning, called Inside the VC and the NVA. 9A Fawcett Columbine book, 1992), now available in paperback. You may just find out why the VC the hundreds of thousands of them who died for their cause did so, probably because they were not from the south but from the North with no where else to go. After a battle when we walked through the battle scene the bodies of the enemy we did find, we often found them to be full of bullets 7-9 each and the soldiers full of heroin. They shot themselves full of heroin so that they would not feel the pain and would keep fighting. Each of them had their plastic black body bags attached, so they could easily be buried. <br>
But that was the war I fought in Vietnam. Not the war depicted in the movies or written about by a college professor that can never understand the silence of the South Vietnamese or the American fighting men during our time. This is contribution to this dialog and my opinion.<br>
With respect<br>
Cook<br>

